    Lake Luzern is super by boat. Scenery is amazing. Go early to avoid the crowds and maybe return by train. For more comfort trave
    We took the 11.12 steamboat from Pier 1 all the way to the far end of the lake at Fluelen. The journey was stunning but at nearly 3 hours it would have been more comfortable in 1st class although I'm not sure how much more expensive it is. We had a Tellpass so rather than head back on the boat we had a nice sandwich in Fluelen and took the train just 3 minutes to Altdorf which is a much more interesting and pretty town with plenty of nice shops which are not open on a Monday though the cafes are. We then took a train back to Luzern which was just one hour and quite a scenic route. The boat from Luzern was very crowded for the first hour so if I did it again I would get an earlier boat

  • Michelle C
    Palo Alto, CA361 contributions
    Quiet museum with amazing modern art collection
    We visited on the morning we left Luzern for about 90 minutes. If you like modern art - an amazing experience. Entry ticket is free with Swiss Travel Pass. The friendly man at reception, who spoke perfect English, greeted us warmly and provided us with an English language guide to carry round (individual painting captions are in German and French). There are free lockers and clean toilets near the entrance. The paintings are well displayed in a light gallery space created from a converted bank building, all marble floors and white walls. The collection on display comprises 30+ paintings, 100+ drawings, and a couple of sculptures by Picasso, with narrative photos by David Douglas Duncan. Paul Klee is represented by over a 100 drawings, watercolors, and oil paintings. There are also paintings by Monet, Cezanne, Renoir etc, and a room devoted to Chagall. The most amazing thing about our visit was that only one other couple was viewing the collection at the same time as us. Like a private viewing.
    Review of: Museum Rosengart Collection

    Beautiful view of Luzern
    To me, the Musegg Wall and its 9 towers are a must visit landmark, alongside the Chapel Bridge and the Lion Monument. This wall was a historical fortification of Luzern in the 13th century.
